    <h2>Why Look Up a VIN Number?</h2>
    <p>A VIN number lookup is one of the most important steps you can take before buying, selling, or insuring a vehicle. The VIN (Vehicle Identification Number) is a unique 17-character code that reveals everything about a vehicle's identity, specifications, and safety history.</p>

    <h2>When to Use a VIN Number Lookup</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Buying a used car:</strong> Verify the seller's claims about the vehicle's year, make, model, and specifications. A VIN lookup can reveal if the vehicle has been misrepresented.</li>
      <li><strong>Checking for safety recalls:</strong> Open recalls mean your vehicle may have a known safety defect. The manufacturer must fix it for free at an authorized dealership.</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance quotes:</strong> Insurance companies use VIN data to accurately quote rates based on your vehicle's exact specifications, safety features, and recall status.</li>
      <li><strong>Selling your vehicle:</strong> Provide potential buyers with a VIN report to build trust and justify your asking price.</li>
      <li><strong>Vehicle registration:</strong> Confirm that VIN records match your title and registration documents.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What Our VIN Lookup Includes</h2>
    <p>When you enter a VIN number, Car Alpha queries the official NHTSA databases to deliver a comprehensive report that includes the make and manufacturer, model name and trim level, model year, engine specifications, body style and drive type, assembly plant location, and any open safety recalls with full campaign details.</p>

    <h2>Free vs. Paid VIN Reports</h2>
    <p>Car Alpha provides free VIN lookups using official government data. This includes vehicle specifications from the NHTSA VPIC database and safety recall data from the NHTSA Office of Defects Investigation. Paid VIN report services like Carfax and AutoCheck offer additional data such as accident history, odometer readings, title status, and ownership history that comes from insurance companies, repair shops, and state DMV records.</p>
